<title>The Hyena&apos;s revenge</title>
<summary><i>The Lion, the Jackal, the Chersina angulata, and the Hyena. By /han≠kass’o (L VIII.-25. 8232-8251). </i>The Lion and the Jackal throw mud at each other and as a result the Lion sits blinded at the water. The |go |go&apos;ken (<i>Chersina angulata, </i>or angulate tortoise) wipes his eyes clean and the Lion eats her, putting her head into his bag. |go |go&apos;ken&apos;s husband, the Hyena, offers the Lion some soup and puts the pot over the Lion&apos;s head and kills him.</summary><comments>1) p.8231v: |han≠kass&apos;o heard this story from his mother (|xabbi-an), 2) pp.8234v-8235v: see <i>An ostrich eggshell, if left open, will attract snakes</i>, 3) p.8235v: what the people call a lion and its movements, 4) p.8236v: the name of a woman; what is said when the white hair of the springbok is &apos;up&apos;; on &apos;dipping up&apos; water when it has rained, 5) p.8241v &amp; 8242v: sorrow and grief (what the |xam and white men say); the drinking of soup, 6) p.8247v: brave men and cowards, 7) p.8250v: a man Tsatsi (|han≠kass&apos;o&apos;s maternal grandfather) told |han≠kass&apos;o about, 8) This story is found in Book VIII-25</comments><date>8 February 1879 (started)</date><storypages>8232-8251</storypages><category>History (Early Race)</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>teasing person</kw><subkw>and the Hyena&apos;s revenge</subkw></keyword>
